  "prompt": "How is WhatsApp able to show the blurred image even after deleting the original copy from the gallery?",
  "response": "WhatsApp employs a few methods to display blurred images even after the original copy has been deleted from a device's gallery. Here are some possibilities:\n\n1. **In-App Caching**: WhatsApp may temporarily cache images within the app itself. When you view an image that has been shared, it is often stored in a cache folder so that it can be displayed quickly without re-downloading it every time. If you delete the original file from your gallery, the cached version can still be used for display purposes within the app.\n\n2. **Image Previews**: When an image is sent or received on WhatsApp, the app generates a thumbnail or a low-resolution version of the image. This thumbnail might remain accessible, even if the original file is deleted from the gallery.\n\n3. **Blurred Previews**: WhatsApp uses a feature where the images are displayed with a blurred effect to serve as a preview. This blurred preview is usually generated only for quick viewing and does not require the original high-resolution image to be present.\n\n4. **Storage Permissions and Retrieval**: Even if the original image is deleted, WhatsApp may have retained permissions to access its own internal storage directories where images are stored temporarily or where cached images reside.\n\nNote that the actual functionality may depend on whether you are using the mobile app or the web version, as well as the specific operating system of your device.",
